instchown: operate on fds, not filenames.

The previous code had been flagged by CodeQL as "TOCTOU". It's not -- at
worst, it's time-of-chown to time-of-chmod -- but this will run more
efficiently (and make the warnings go away).

commit.message:
Simply triggering builds on push is sufficient.

We expect merging a PR to run autobuilds on the target branch (e.g.,
master). The recent autobuild improvements caused a regression here:
merging a PR has lately been running autobuilds on the *source* branch.
So GitHub has no information to offer about build status on master,
which also confounds the status badge recently added to README.md.

As we suspected, I had overengineered the trigger constraints. Merging a
PR causes the target branch to receive a push, we don't need to treat
any branches (or PRs!) specially in autobuilds, and the branch
protection rules already in place for master -- together with running
builds on every branch push -- are sufficient for PR merges to be as
safe as they've always been.
Link build-status badge to master-branch runs.
Don't generate empty catpages by mistake.

tests: fix array sorting on big endian 64 bit

The array elements are unsigned long, i.e. 64 bit on such arches. When casting
them to int only the lower half would be compared, which doesn't matter on
32 bit arches or little endian, but fails on 64 bit BE as s390 or sparc.

commit.message:
allow additional groups for qmail-remote

Common patches add e.g. DKIM signing or TLS encryption also for remote
processes. Until now you could only have these files belong to group qmail,
which collides with the claim "these programs don't even trust each other" from
SECURITY.md, or make them world readable, which is even worse.

Honor all groups the qmailr user is part of when spawning qmail-rspawn. This
allows constructs like:

-primary group qmail: the queue can be read
-secondary group qmailcert: the TLS certificates can be read, and qmail-smtpd
 can share that group membership
-third group qmailr: the DKIM keys
